  "prompt": "Programming Languages: What was the first REPL?",
  "response": "The first REPL (Read-Eval-Print Loop) is widely considered to be the **Lisp interpreter**.\n\nSpecifically, the original Lisp interpreter developed by John McCarthy and his team at MIT in the late 1950s and early 1960s. While it wasn't necessarily called a \"REPL\" back then, it functioned in the same way:\n\n*   **Read:** The interpreter would read a Lisp expression from the input.\n*   **Eval:** It would evaluate that expression.\n*   **Print:** It would print the result of the evaluation.\n*   **Loop:** It would then return to the read step, creating a continuous loop.\n\nThis interactive mode of operation was a key characteristic of Lisp from its inception and significantly contributed to its popularity and use in AI research and development. It allowed programmers to quickly experiment with code, test ideas, and debug programs in a very interactive and iterative way.\n",
